A regular octagon $ABCDEFGH$ has an area of one square unit. What is the area of the rectangle  $ABEF$?

[asy]
pair A,B,C,D,I,F,G,H;
A=(-1,1);
B=(1,1);
H=(-2.41,-0.41);
C=(2.41,-0.41);
G=(-2.41,-2.41);
D=(2.41,-2.41);
F=(-1,-3.82);
I=(1,-3.82);
draw(A--B--C--D--I--F--G--H--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,N);
label("$C$",C,E);
label("$D$",D,E);
label("$E$",I,S);
label("$F$",F,S);
label("$G$",G,W);
label("$H$",H,W);
[/asy]

solution:
Let $O$ be the intersection of the diagonals of $ABEF$. Since the octagon is regular, $\triangle AOB$ has area $1/8$. Since $O$ is the midpoint of $\overline{AE}$, $\triangle OAB$ and $\triangle
BOE$ have the same area. Thus  $\triangle ABE$ has area $1/4$, so $ABEF$ has area $\boxed{\frac{1}{2}}$. [asy]
pair A,B,C,D,I,F,G,H;
A=(-1,1);
B=(1,1);
H=(-2.41,-0.41);
C=(2.41,-0.41);
G=(-2.41,-2.41);
D=(2.41,-2.41);
F=(-1,-3.82);
I=(1,-3.82);
draw(A--B--C--D--I--F--G--H--cycle,linewidth(0.7));
label("$A$",A,N);
label("$B$",B,N);
label("$C$",C,E);
label("$D$",D,E);
label("$E$",I,S);
label("$F$",F,S);
label("$G$",G,W);
label("$H$",H,W);
draw(A--F);
draw(B--I);
draw(A--I,dashed);
draw(B--F,dashed);
label("$o$",(0,-1.42),E);
[/asy]

Name the vertices of the hexagon so that hexagon $ABCDEF$ has $AB=1$, $BC=7$, $CD=2$, and $DE=4$.  The hexagon is equiangular, so each interior angle measures $180(6-2)/6=120$ degrees.  Extend sides $AB$, $CD$, and $EF$ and call their intersection points $G$, $H$, and $J$ as shown.  The exterior angles of the hexagon each measure $180-120=60$ degrees, so triangles $JDE$, $CBH$, $FGA$, and $JHG$ are all equilateral.  It follows that $JD=DE=4$ units and $CH=CB=7$ units.  Therefore the side length $JH$ of triangle $JGH$ is $4+2+7=13$ units.  Turning to side $HG$, we find that $AF=AG=13-(7+1)=5$ units.  Finally, we solve $JG=JE+EF+FG$ for $EF$ to get $EF=13-(4+5)=4$ units.  The sum of the missing sides is $5+4=\boxed{9}$ units.

[asy]
size(6cm);
defaultpen(linewidth(.7pt)+fontsize(8pt));
dotfactor=4;

pair A=(8,0), B=(7,0), C=7*dir(60), D=9*dir(60), Ep=(13,0)+9*dir(120), F=(13,0)+5*dir(120), G=(13,0), H=(0,0), J=13*dir(60);

pair[] dots = {A, B, C, D, Ep, F};

dot(dots);

draw(A--B--C--D--Ep--F--cycle);

draw(B--H--C,dashed);
draw(D--J--Ep,dashed);
draw(F--G--A,dashed);

label("$A$",A,S);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("$C$",C,NW);
label("$D$",D,NW);
label("$E$",Ep,NE);
label("$F$",F,NE);
label("$G$",G,SE);
label("$H$",H,SW);
label("$J$",J,N);

label("$1$",(A+B)/2,N);
label("$7$",(B+C)/2,NE);
label("$2$",(C+D)/2,SE);
label("$4$",(D+Ep)/2,S);
[/asy]

By the Binomial Theorem, we have  \begin{align*}
301^4 &= (3(100) + 1)^4\\
&= \binom40 \cdot 3^4 \cdot 100^4 \cdot 1^0 + \binom41 \cdot 3^3 \cdot 100^3 \cdot 1^1 \\
&\qquad\qquad+ \binom42 \cdot 3^2 \cdot 100^2 \cdot 1^2+ \binom43 \cdot 3^1 \cdot 100^1 \cdot 1^3 \\
&\qquad\qquad+ \binom44 \cdot 3^0 \cdot 100^0 \cdot 1^4.
\end{align*} All but the last two terms are divisible by $10000=100^2$, so we only have to consider the remainder when the last two terms are divided by 10,000. The last two terms are  \begin{align*}
\binom43 &\cdot 3^1 \cdot 100^1 \cdot 1^3 + \binom44 \cdot 3^0 \cdot 100^0 \cdot 1^4\\
&= 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 100 \cdot 1 + 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1 \cdot 1\\
& = 1200 + 1 = \boxed{1201}.\end{align*}

By the angle bisector theorem, $AC/CD = AB/BD = 105/42 = 5/2$.  Let $AC = 5x$ and $CD = 2x$.

[asy]
unitsize(0.03 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;

A = (0,105);
B = (0,0);
C = (100,0);
D = (42,0);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(A--D);

label("$A$", A, NW);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$42$", (B + D)/2, S);
label("$105$", (A + B)/2, W);
label("$2x$", (C + D)/2, S);
label("$5x$", (A + C)/2, NE);
[/asy]

Then by Pythagoras, $(2x + 42)^2 + 105^2 = (5x)^2$.  This simplifies to $21x^2 - 168x - 12789 = 0$, which factors as $21(x - 29)(x + 21) = 0$, so $x = 29$.  Therefore, $AC = 5x = \boxed{145}$.

